        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will use the spectral scan mode with five spectral tunings to cover the frequency range from 221 to 255 GHz, to search for
redshifted [CII] line from z = 6.45 to 7.60. The aim is to detect the [CII] line, so we do not request high angular resolution to
resolve the source. Given that typical z&gt;6 objects have sub-arcsec size in high-resolution HST images, we thus request a 1 arcsec
resolution to detect the line without beam dilution.

The stellar mass of our target is less than 10^10 Msun, which is not very massive comparing to other molecular line-detected luminous 
galaxies at z&lt;6. Therefore we do not expect a very borad line. Here we assume a line width of 200 km/s. In the science justification, we
estimate the line flux to be 0.23-0.28 Jy km/s in the redshift range of our interest. Here we adopt the lower bound of 0.23 Jy km/s. 
This leads to a mean line flux density of 1.15 mJy within the 200 km/s width. For our redshift search, we require an S/N of 8 to 
securely identify the line. However, given the scatter of the [CII] luminosity at a given IR luminosity (Fig. 3), it is possible for the
line to be weaker than this. In the case where the line is ~40% weaker, we still have a minimally acceptable S/N of 5. This leads 
to the sensitivity requirement of rms = 0.144 mJy.

We will smooth the channels to a velocity resolution of ~9.8 km/s. This will significantly reduce the data rate but still provide
sufficient resolution for our studies.

**** We notice that the overhead here is unusually large, much larger than what it is required to do the five scans separately.  We hope the actual observation will have a higher efficiency.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
