    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Finding galaxies at z &gt; 7 has profound implication to the understanding of the early assembly history of galaxies and the reionization history in the universe. A key difficulty here is that z &gt; 7 galaxy candidates found in various ultra deep near-IR images are hard to confirm with near-IR spectroscopy, because of the effects of IGM and ISM absorption, as well as the strong emission from earth's atmosphere. The unprecedented sensitivity of ALMA provides an alternative route to this challenging task: [CII] line search. [CII] is the most important ISM cooling line in the far-IR and is &gt;1000x stronger than CO. In ALMA Early Science, [CII] lines have been detected from various high-redshift galaxy populations. Here we propose to conduct a pilot ALMA Band-6 [CII] search on a remarkable luminous z~7 galaxy candidate in the Hubble Ultra Deep Field. This galaxy is unanimously agreed by many groups to be a galaxy at z~7. VLT spectroscopy also tentatively detected a Lyman alpha line at &gt;3 sigma independently by two groups. Detecting [CII] from this galaxy using ALMA's spectral scan mode is an essential step toward future ALMA studies on a larger sample of fainter z&gt;7 galaxies.</prp:abstract>
